SecurityProfile.Name: Base Policy - Trend Micro
SecurityProfile.Description:
## Don't add server/endpoints to this policy level Version: 2024-05-24 This is a best effort base policy, it's not the final policy and this policy needs to be configured according to the customer needs before being used.
All config in these policies is based on Trend Micro Best Practice for Deep Security/Workload Security and from Microsofts recommendations according antimalware exclusions. See sources below.
* https://help.deepsecurity.trendmicro.com/Deep_Security_20_Best_Practice_Guide.pdf
* https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-365/security/defender-endpoint/configure-server-exclusions-microsoft-defender-antivirus?view=o365-worldwide#list-of-automatic-exclusions
## Change log 2024-05-24 * Updated standard Windows exclusions * Added IIS Web Policy * Added multiple exclusion lists at Policy level
2024-05-03 * Non blocking policies added under Toolbox "Non-blocking (Detection Only)" * Trend Non-Blocking Realtime/Schedule Scan Configuration
2024-01-31 * Security Investigation policies added for Windows/Linux - Apply to a computer when more extensive monitoring of a system is required during a suspected security breach
2023-11-14 * Set Activity Monitoring default OFF on all policies
2023-06-01 * Changed all Windows Antimalware Scan Interface (AMSI) settings to Terminate
2023-03-01 * Remove some exclusions from Exchange 2019 Directory/Process lists based on new Microsoft AV recommendations * Changed "Automatically implement Intrusion Prevention Recommendations:" to NO for Windows Endpoints Polices * Changed "Implement core Endpoint & Workload rules automatically:" to YES on endpoint policies
2023-01-23 * Added new policies for Windows Endpoints and Windows Servers
## Change log 2022-12-20 * Changed to "${windir}\Temp\OICE_*\" in Exchange directory list

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Installed software attributes modified (ATT&CK T1195.002, T1554)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is any change in attributes of installed software or program attributes. Also it alerts when a program is installed or uninstalled on windows host. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: Also the rule provides configuration options to ignore monitoring software and to select the InstalledSoftware and RegistryKey attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Software installed, updated or removed
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when software is installed or uninstalled on the target host. The rule monitors software which is registered using RPM packages on Linux and pkginfo on Solaris. For additional information, see the Details tab

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Attributes of services modified (ATT&CK T1036.004, T1543.003)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule is intended to alert when attributes of certain services are modified. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule also provides configuration options to ignore monitoring services.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - File permissions in the /var/log directory modified (ATT&CK T1222.002)
IntegrityRule.Description:
Adversaries may modify permissions to access to log files and with appropriate permissions can delete the activity/attack logs to evade the detection. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: Configuration options are provided to exclude certain files and directories.

IntegrityRule.Name: TMTR-0018: Suspicious Files Detected In User Profile Directory (ATT&CK T1560.001)

This rule is applicable to Windows platforms.

IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors the execution of the command prompt. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Systemd service modified (ATT&CK T1543.002)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors changes systemd services. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - bash root user configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1546.004)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries can insert code into the files listed in the details tab to gain persistence each time a user logs in or opens a new shell. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Task scheduler entries modified (ATT&CK T1053)
IntegrityRule.Description:
An adversary may use job scheduling to execute programs at system startup or on a scheduled basis for persistence, to conduct execution as part of lateral movement, to gain root privileges or to run a process under the context of a specific account. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: Configuration option are provided to exclude certain tasks and directories, and to disable the monitoring for cron jobs processes.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Network services registries modified (ATT&CK T1547.001, T1574.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by adding a program to a startup folder or may execute their own malicious payloads by hijacking the search order used to load DLLs. This rule monitors such registry keys which can be used for the persistence. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - AutoRun registries modified (ATT&CK T1547.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by adding a program to a startup folder or referencing it with a Registry run key. This rule monitors registry keys and values which can be used to set startup folder items for persistence. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Boot or Logon Autostart Execution registries modified (ATT&CK T1547.004, T1547.014)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may modify Winlogon registries to execute DLLs and/or executables when a user logs in or modify registry key to the Active Setup of the local machine for the persistence. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Autostart execution registries modified (ATT&CK T1547.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by adding a program to a startup folder or referencing it with a Registry run key. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Files in appdata startup folder modified (ATT&CK T1547.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by placing a program within a startup folder. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - System File Modified
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is change in attributes of system files like boot.ini, ntldr, autorun.inf, files with com, exe, bat, ocx, pif, sys extension located under %SystemDrive% (e.g. C:) directory. By default we ignore monitoring pagefile.sys and hiberfil.sys files.
Also the rule provides configuration option to ignore files for monitoring and to select the file attributes to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Files in start menu directory modified (ATT&CK T1547.001)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may achieve persistence by placing a program within a startup folder. For additional information, see the Details tab.

This rule alerts when there is a change in file attributes under monitored directories. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to select the file attributes that should be monitored and also paths to ignore. It has the potential to monitor a large number of files and also generate large number of events and so exceptions should be configured carefully.

IntegrityRule.Name: Application - Trend Micro Deep Security Agent / Relay
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alert indicates that the files / registry keys / services created by Deep Security Agent / Relay were modified. This could indicate that the software was updated or installed / uninstalled.
On windows, the rule look into any change made to installedSoftware, files, directories, registry and services.
On Unix, it monitors installedSoftware, files, directories and process changes.
The rule also provides interface to configure installation file path.
Note: onChange feature will not work for the DirectorySet entity set in this rule.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Users and Groups - Create and Delete Activity (ATT&CK T1136)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule detects creation and deletion of users and groups. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: Configuration option is provided to exclude users and groups to monitor.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - adduser, useradd and deluser configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1136.001, T1531)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may manipulate the default configuration of "adduser", "useradd" and "deluser" commands for the persistence. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Alternative commands modified (ATT&CK T1036)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors files in "/etc/alternatives" directory that is used to keep track of the alternatives currently in use, by a tool called update-alternatives. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - System .dll or .exe files modified (ATT&CK T1036.003, T1222.001)

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - bash configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1059.004, T1546.004)

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - SSH client configuration modified (ATT&CK1021.004)

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Task scheduler entries modified (ATT&CK T1053.005)
IntegrityRule.Description: An adversary may use job scheduling to execute programs at system startup or on a scheduled basis for persistence, to conduct execution as part of lateral movement, to gain root privileges, or to run a process under the context of a specific account. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - SSH server configuration file modified (ATT&CK T1021.004)

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - bash command history cleared (ATT&CK T1059.004)
IntegrityRule.Description:

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Internet routing information file modified
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors "etc/gateways" file which specify Internet routing information to routed daemon. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - SSH authorized_keys file modified - systemwide (ATT&CK T1021.004, T1098.004, T1563.001)

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Local user and group files modified (ATT&CK T1136.001, T1531)

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Name resolver configuration files modified (ATT&CK T1071.004, T1583.002)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule monitors the configuration files which are responsible for DNS resolution. This rule will not get assigned by a recommendation scan. It should be assigned only to hosts where the monitored files do not change outside a maintenance window. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Root Certificate Registry keys modified (ATT&CK T1553.004)
IntegrityRule.Description: Installation of a root certificate on a compromised system would give an adversary a way to degrade the security of that system. Adversaries have used this technique to avoid security warnings prompting users when compromised systems connect over HTTPS to adversary controlled web servers that spoof legitimate websites in order to collect login credentials. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - USB storage device detected (ATT&CK T1052.001, T1092)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when a USB storage device is plugged in the system. It monitors the changes in registry key to detect the attachment and removal of USB storage device. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: Linux/Unix - Software repository modified (ATT&CK T1195.002)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may manipulate the package repository list for the purpose of compromising data or the system. For additional information, see the Details tab.

IntegrityRule.Name: TMTR-0012: Suspicious Files Detected In Temporary Directories (ATT&CK T1560.001)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This generic rule is intended to alert when highly suspicious malware specific file entity is created or modified.
This rule is applicable to Windows platforms.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Rename Activity Over Network Share - Client
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SMB rename operations over the network.The rule will detect the number of SMB file rename operations during the defined number of seconds. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation on SMB shares for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: The rule also has configuration option to exclude the IPs of the SMB Shares where renames operation can be performed by client machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reflected File Download Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Reflected File Download (RFD) is a web attack vector that enables attackers to gain complete control over a user system. In an RFD attack, the user follows a malicious link to a trusted domain resulting in a file download from that domain.
Note: Configuration option is provided to add the executable file extensions to block the RFD attack for the file extensions. Administrators are suggested to add executable file extensions to block the RFD attack according to their Web Application file extension support. The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm their domain are being used to carry out RFD attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Pastebin Communication (ATT&CK T1102.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying commands to a compromised system. This filter detects web access to Pastebein service.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Redhat Webshell C&C Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Ransomware Cryptesla
PayloadFilter2.Description: Cryptesla (also known as TeslaCrypt) is a Trojan from a ransomware family and this Trojan arrives on a system as a file dropped by other malware or as a file downloaded unknowingly by users when visiting malicious sites. It connects to certain websites to send and receive information. This DPI rule detects such HTTP communication between the Trojan and it's Command and Control servers.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Attempt For DNS Snooping
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule detects the possible attempt of snooping on a DNS server for the existence of records in the cache.
Note: Triggers from this DPI rule should be investigated further to confirm attacks. Configuration options are provided to customize the event frequency.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trickbot Data Exfiltration - (Application Credentials Grabber)

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Too Many DNS Responses With 'No Such Name' Error
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is based on heuristics. Too many DNS responses with 'no Such Name' error within a specific amount of time is suspicious and should be investigated thoroughly. The rule can be configured by the Deep Security administrator.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified FTP Backdoor.Win32.Qbot.JINX Runtime Detection
PayloadFilter2.Description: Backdoor.Win32.Qbot.JINX is a bot agent that targets the Windows platform. This malware collects a plethora of information from the infected system and sends it to a remote server. Moreover, it steals login credentials for different targeted systems and services. Furthermore, the malware can monitor user's online activities, inject code into target websites, steal banking credentials, download additional plugins, and provide remote access among other nefarious activities. To survive a system reboot, it creates a scheduled task.

PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects the usage of suspicious SMB command used to create covert channels in SMB. This kind of attack is used by attack payloads like doublepulsar.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious China Chopper Webshell Communication (ATT&CK T1505.003)
PayloadFilter2.Description: China Chopper Webshell is a malware designed to remotely access Windows or Linux Web servers. The malware has a Web shell command-and-control (CnC) client binary and a text-based Web shell payload (server component). Post infection, the malware enables remote attackers to execute arbitrary code on affected systems. This is a heuristic based rule which detects the HTTP communication of China chopper Webshell.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Cobalt Strike Malleable C&C Traffic Response (YouTube Profile)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Alert for this DPI Filter is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Cobalt Strike Beacon C&C HTTP communications could be customized with what's known as malleable C2 profiles. Those profiles are meant to mimic legitimate services requests, such as, Amazon, Google and Office 365, among others, for the purpose of hiding malicious traffic. Moreover, they could be also used for emulating a known malware C&C traffic.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file create, write and delete operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Command Injection Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Command injection is an attack technique that allows an attacker to inject and execute commands in the vulnerable application. An attacker can exploit command injection vulnerability with a command sequence appended to the appropriate format or escape string to execute arbitrary commands. Successful exploitation results in a system compromise, disclosure or modification of data. This is a heuristic based rule to block command injection attacks. In some network environment further investigation will be required to confirm the attack.
Note: Configuration options are provided to configure the parameter names where commands are allowed.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of An Archive File (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of Archive files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.
Note: Configuration options have been provided to select the file extensions. Without configuration rule will not be able to identify the upload of any kind of archive files.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMB DLL Injection Exploit Detected (ATT&CK T1055.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is based on heuristics and will detect dll injection attack is being performed using SMB share. This rule could generate many alerts on some network environment hence each trigger needs further investigation to ensure attack.
Note: This rule only detects traffic and does not block.

PayloadFilter2.Description: An XML file with external entity reference may allow remote attacker to read the contents of a file on a target system or open or TCP connections. This rule identify the download of XML files which has External Entity Reference over HTTP.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) Connection Request
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to identify Remote Desktop connection request using Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP). In some network environment, many RDP connection requests, could lead to Denial of Service (DOS) condition.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to: 1- customize the number of requests and the time interval. After the frequency of RDP connection requests matched as per the configuration, the rule will prevent any further RDP connection from the same Source IP for the configured period of time. 2- set the IP(s) of trusted host(s) to pass traffic.

After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation from that source for the defined period of time.

After the malicious source is detected, the rule will prevent any further malicious SMB file rename and write operations from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions for specific IPs of the client machines doing rename operations.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Backdoor.Win32.Cobalt.SMHP C&C Traffic Request

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Bash ShellShock Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Bash is prone to a remote code execution vulnerability when it incorrectly processes trailing strings after certain malformed function definitions in the values of environment variables, which allows remote attackers to write to files or possibly have unknown other impact via a crafted request. This is a heuristic based rule to detect such attacks.
Note: In some network environment this rule could generate many alerts, hence every trigger should be investigated further to confirm the attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trojan-Downloader.Win32.Cometer.bfc C&C Traffic Request
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based DPI rule to detect Indicators of Compromise related to a vulnerability in MS Word (CVE-2014-1761) which is getting exploited in the wild. It detects a static self-signed certificate used by the backdoor on the compromised machine to communicate with the remote C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS - 1 (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between the compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Vkontakte Site Access Over HTTP (ATT&CK T1102.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying commands to a compromised system. This filter detects an attempt to access the Vkontakte website.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potential Malicious Client Traffic (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to prevent potentially harmful traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Image With Embedded PHP Code
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is a heuristic based rule to detect malicious php code embedded within gif, jpg and png image files. An attacker may use maliciously crafted image file to do remote code execution and take control of the victim's host machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potential Malicious Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to prevent potentially harmful traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Generic PHP Webshell Payload Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Local File Inclusion (LFI) Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects Local File Inclusion (LFI) in HTTP request. Local File Include is an attack technique used to exploit "dynamic file include" mechanisms in web applications. When web applications take user input and pass them into file include commands, the web application might be tricked into including local files with malicious code.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the DPI rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Ransomware TCP Request-1

PayloadFilter2.Name: Radmin Server Remote Control Session Setup (ATT&CK T1219)

PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote code execution vulnerability exists in the way that the Microsoft Windows handles the loading of DLL files. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could take complete control of an affected system. This rule is based on heuristics and will only detect DLL file being accessed over SMB share. Hence this rule should be applied when DLL files are not used over the network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: VNC Client (ATT&CK T1076,T1219)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects VNC client traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Order Of CNAME And DNAME Records In Query Response (CVE-2017-3137)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
ISC BIND is vulnerable to a denial-of-service condition when parsing a request containing the CNAME and the DNAME records in an unusual order. A remote attacker could use this flaw to make Bind sevice exit unexpectedly with an assertion failure via a specially crafted DNS response. This heuristic based DPI rule detects an unusual order of the CNAME and the DNAME records in the DNS Query response.
Note: This rule could give multiple triggers on some network environment, therefore each trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Ransomware Locky
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects HTTP communication between Locky ransomware and its Command and Control Server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Apache Linux/Cdorked HTTP Request Cookie Header
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is intended to detect a crafted HTTP request Cookie header which was used in the recent Apache Backdoor, Linux/Cdorked.A. The backdoor redirects traffic to malicious websites by crafting web Cookie header. Successful attacks enables remote attackers to get the full root access to the server from modifying configurations, to injecting modules and replacing binaries.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote code execution vulnerability exists in the Microsoft Windows Shell. Windows incorrectly parses shortcuts in such a way that malicious code may be executed when the user clicks the displayed icon of a specially crafted shortcut.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trickbot Data Exfiltration (Network Module)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Trickbot is a banking stealer Trojan that targets the Windows platform. The malware communicates over SSL/TLS channel, however, one of its module, and in particular, the network module, communicates over HTTP. This module is responsible for collecting plethora of system information and sending it to a remote server. Collected information includes, list of all running processes, OS, user and domain specific information, among others.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Trickbot Data Exfiltration (Card Payment)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Trickbot is a banking stealer Trojan that targets the Windows platform. The malware communicates over SSL/TLS channel, however, some of its modules communicate over HTTP. This filter covers the module that steals payment card data and sends it to a remote C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Web Client Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter to detect HTTP Client traffic by using Wget and Curl user agent. For mission critical servers, limited HTTP client traffic means those servers will have less exposure to web related attacks. It also prevents potential backdoor software from contacting external malicious sites.
This filter will be triggered once per minute for a given host. The frequency of event settings can be modified on the Configuration tab should your environment require different configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Cobalt Strike Malleable C&C Traffic Request (Office 365 Calendar Profile)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Alert for this DPI Filter is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Cobalt Strike Beacon C&C HTTP communications could be customized with what's known as malleable C2 profiles. Those profiles are meant to mimic legitimate services requests, such as, Amazon, Google and Office 365, among others, for the purpose of hiding malicious traffic. Moreover, they could be also used for emulating a known malware C&C traffic.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SMB rename operations over the network. The rule will detect the number of SMB file rename operations during the defined number of seconds. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: The rule also has configuration option to exclude the IPs of the client machines doing rename operations.

The protocol itself is derived from the Open Software Foundation (OSF) RPC protocol.
